		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Write content";
		$task->body = '<h2>1. Treat your web visitors like wild animals</h2><p>Your website visitors behave like wild animals (source: <a href=\"http://www.nngroup.com/articles/information-scent/\" target=\"_blank\">Jakob Nielsen&rsquo;s Alertbox</a>).</p><p>They&rsquo;re hunting for information or a product to buy &ndash; just like a hungry panther hunts for his next meal.</p><p>When a panther sniffs a scent trail he quickly decides: will the scent trail lead to a good meal? And will it be an easy catch?</p><p>Your web visitors consider the same two things: Does your website offer what they&rsquo;re looking for? And can they find it easily?</p><p>A hungry panther doesn&rsquo;t like wasting time to catch a meal. And your web visitors don&rsquo;t want to browse around your website for several long minutes to find the product they&rsquo;re after. They want to find it quickly.</p><p>Just like the panther makes a fast decision whether to follow a scent trail or not, your web visitor decides quickly whether your site is useful or not. So if your site looks complicated with a lot of options to choose from, they click away to check out another website.</p><p>Web visitors quickly glance at your web page before guessing whether they&rsquo;re in the right place or not. They don&rsquo;t need to know for sure. They just want to make a quick decision.</p><p>If your web visitors only glance at your website, how do you get your message across?</p><h2>2. Put your most important information first</h2><p>&nbsp;</p><div id=\"attachment_1917\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><span class=\"sw-pinit\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1917\" src=\"http://enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/old-fashioned-essays.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" srcset=\"http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/old-fashioned-essays.jpg 300w, http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/old-fashioned-essays-120x83.jpg 120w, http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/old-fashioned-essays-250x174.jpg 250w\" alt=\"Old looking papers and pen\" width=\"300\" height=\"209\" /></span><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Don&rsquo;t write a web page like an old-fashion essay. Mention your most important information first.</p></div><p>Writing for the web is completely different than writing an essay or a paper.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>An essay might go like this: First, explain what you&rsquo;re going to discuss. Then, present an overview of the literature. Next, discuss; and finally draw your conclusion. The most important point you make is in the conclusion &ndash; at the end of your essay!</p><p>On web pages you have to do the opposite: your most important points always come first.</p><p>An example: you&rsquo;re looking for a new red three-seater sofa. When you arrive at a website you want to see it sells sofas. And secondly, you want a search box so you know you can quickly find out what the red three-seater sofas are like.</p><p>Or say you&rsquo;re looking for a copywriter for your website. Maybe you&rsquo;re looking for someone local, so you need to see a copywriter is based in Manchester which is nearby. Or maybe your copywriter needs to understand medical terminology, so you like to see a headline like<em>copywriting for the medical industry</em>.</p><p>Information that&rsquo;s most important to your web visitors is often a simple statement of what you do. Once they understand what you do, they might want to know some important details. And then &ndash; maybe they&rsquo;d like to know some background information.</p><p>Journalists call this way of writing <strong>the inverted pyramid</strong>. In newspaper articles the most newsworthy information comes first before details and background information. Even if you only read the first paragraph of a newspaper story you still understand the big picture.</p><p>It&rsquo;s the same on your website. Your customers want to know the big picture first. Basically: What do you do? Or what can you do for them?</p><h2>3. Don&rsquo;t try to be clever or creative</h2><p>On the web it&rsquo;s rare that a reader hangs on to every word you write. He doesn&rsquo;t have time. He&rsquo;s in a hurry because he could check out several other <em>scent trails</em> &ndash; websites &ndash; instead of wasting time trying to figure out what you do.</p><p>Simple statements often work best.</p><blockquote><p>[W]hen I look at a Web page it should be self-evident. Obvious. Self-explanatory. ~ <a href=\"http://www.sensible.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Steve Krug</a>.</p></blockquote><p>Clever phrasing requires people to think. And asking people to think, doesn&rsquo;t work on the web because web visitors are hunting &ndash; they don&rsquo;t have time to think. So keep your web copy as simple as possible.</p><p>Write as if you&rsquo;re writing for a 12-year old because that makes your copy easy-to-follow. And be careful with jokes unless you&rsquo;re absolutely sure your target audience will get them.</p><h2>4. Write for scanners</h2><p>How many people read web pages?</p><p>Hardly anybody!</p><blockquote><p>[What most web visitors do] is glance at each new page, scan some of the text, and click on the first link that catches their interest or vaguely resembles the thing they&rsquo;re looking for. &ndash; <a href=\"http://www.sensible.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Steve Krug</a></p></blockquote><p>Research suggests that only 16% of people read web pages word-for-word. Most people scan. (source: <a href=\"http://www.nngroup.com/articles/how-users-read-on-the-web/\" target=\"_blank\">Jakob Nielsen&rsquo;s Alertbox</a>).</p><p>How can you write for scanners? A check list:</p><ul><li>Does your headline communicate what you&rsquo;re about?</li><li>Does your image caption communicate a sales message?</li><li>Do your sub headlines summarize your key points?</li><li>Do easy-to-scan bullet points reduce <a href=\"http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/how-to-avoid-wordiness/\">wordiness</a>?</li></ul><p>Your web visitor is hunting for information or products. Ensure he can understand your most important information by <a href=\"http://enchantingmarketing.com/website-billboard/\">just glancing at your web page</a>.</p><h2>5. Use familiar words</h2><blockquote><p>As Web readers, we are hunter-gatherers once again &ndash; only this time, instead of scanning the horizon for prey, we scan pages for <strong>carewords</strong>. When we see these words, we click, we act. ~ <a href=\"http://www.gerrymcgovern.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Gerry McGovern</a></p></blockquote><p>Imagine you want to fly to Bangkok for a holiday and you&rsquo;re looking for a cheap flight. What will you search for: a cost-effective flight, a low-fare, or a cheap flight to Bangkok?</p><p>Nobody searches for cost-effective flights. As <a href=\"https://adwords.google.com/o/Targeting/Explorer?__c=1000000000&amp;__u=1000000000&amp;ideaRequestType=KEYWORD_IDEAS\" target=\"_blank\">Google&rsquo;s Keyword Tool</a>shows cheap is what people are looking for:</p><div id=\"attachment_1901\" class=\"wp-caption aligncentre\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1901\" src=\"http://enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/low-cost-flight-searches.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 362px) 100vw, 362px\" srcset=\"http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/low-cost-flight-searches.jpg 362w, http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/low-cost-flight-searches-120x41.jpg 120w, http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/low-cost-flight-searches-250x86.jpg 250w\" alt=\"Keyword search results showing cheap is far more popular than low fare and cost effective\" width=\"362\" height=\"125\" /><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Most people search for cheap flights</p></div><p>Carewords are the words people are looking for. We often like to make ourselves sound better than we are. We try to embellish what we do. We try to sound scientific, fancy or special. But your web visitor is looking for familiar words &ndash; carewords &ndash; because they&rsquo;re the scent trail that tells him he&rsquo;s in the right place.</p><h2>6. Write for lazy people</h2><p>Just like the lazy panther looks for an easy catch for his dinner, your web visitor doesn&rsquo;t want to make an effort to read your text.</p><p>Make your copy easy to read:</p><ul><li>Use short paragraphs &ndash; four sentences max;</li><li>Use short sentences &ndash; twelve on average;</li><li>Skip unnecessary words;</li><li>Avoid jargon and gobbledygook;</li><li>Avoid the passive tense;</li><li>Avoid needless repetition;</li><li>Address your web visitors directly. Use the word you;</li><li>Shorten your text.</li></ul><p>How short should your text be? Steve Krug recommends you get rid of half the words on each page, and then get rid of half of what&rsquo;s left. That maybe an overly demanding target, but give it a go. Set yourself a challenge and make your text as short as possible.</p><h2>7. Expect people to arrive anywhere on your website</h2><p>&nbsp;</p><div id=\"attachment_1914\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1914\" src=\"http://enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/reading-a-book-from-front-to-back.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" srcset=\"http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/reading-a-book-from-front-to-back.jpg 300w, http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/reading-a-book-from-front-to-back-120x77.jpg 120w, http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/reading-a-book-from-front-to-back-250x161.jpg 250w\" alt=\"woman reading a book\" width=\"300\" height=\"194\" /><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Your website isn&rsquo;t read from <br />start to finish like a book. (<a href=\"http://clicktotweet.com/8nWxt\" target=\"_blank\">tweet this</a>)</p></div><p>People usually read a book from chapter one, via chapter two to three and four etc.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Now, imagine people pick up a book and start reading somewhere completely at random. Possibly at the beginning of the last chapter, maybe in the middle of chapter three, or at the last page of chapter one.</p><p>That&rsquo;s what the web is like. Most web visitors will not start reading at your home page. They may arrive on any of your web pages.</p><div class=\"highlight\">If you don&rsquo;t know where people arrive on your website, go to Google Analytics &gt;&gt; Site Content &gt;&gt; Landing Pages. You can see exactly how many web visitors arrived on each web page.</div><p>If each web page can be an entry page what does that mean?</p><ul><li>Each page should be easy to scan;</li><li>Each page should clarify to people where they are; and what your site is about;</li><li>Each page should have a call to action telling people where to go next &ndash; to read another blog post, sign up for your email newsletter, check out a detailed product description or testimonial, request a quote or add a product to a shopping cart.</li></ul><p>Don&rsquo;t rely on your navigation bar to tell people what to do next. Include a button or link to guide people to take the next step. On each page.</p><h2>8. Make it easy for hunters to find you</h2><p>Potential customers are hunting for information or products.</p><p>How can you help them find you?</p><p>Lure potential customers <a href=\"http://www.enchantingmarketing.com/web-content-checklist/\">to your website by providing useful information</a>. That&rsquo;s how <a href=\"http://enchantingmarketing.com/seo-friendly-blog-posts/\">writing for SEO </a>(Search Engine Optimization) basically works:</p><ul><li>Answer the questions potential customers are asking;</li><li>Discuss one key topic for each page;</li><li>Include links to relevant pages on your own website or to other websites;</li><li>Use phrases and words your potential customers are looking for.</li></ul><p>Above all: Be helpful.</p><h2>9. Make a visual impression</h2><p>Web copy and web design should work together.</p><p>You can&rsquo;t write your words, you can&rsquo;t compose your sentences, you can create your bullet points, without considering how your web page will look.</p><p>The visual appeal of your website impacts the readability of your text; and influences whether web visitors can quickly get what you&rsquo;re about.</p><p>How to increase the visual appeal of your web copy:</p><ul><li>Replace text by photographs or videos;</li><li>Consider different font sizes &ndash; think about people scanning large text first;</li><li>Emphasize quotes of customers (or experts) to add credibility;</li><li>Play around with highlights, <strong>bold text</strong>, CAPS, or <em>italics</em>;</li><li>Break a long headline into a headline with a sub headline;</li><li>Change paragraphs into bullet points.</li></ul><p>Most importantly: de-clutter. Reduce noise and add white space. Not only will it make your website easier to read, it will also increase your perceived trust (source: <a href=\"http://socialtriggers.com/content-is-king-myth/\" target=\"_blank\">Social Triggers</a>).</p><h2>The truth about writing persuasive web copy</h2><p>I&rsquo;d love to tell you that writing persuasive web copy is easy.</p><p>But the truth is that writing simple, useful copy is hard.</p><p>Don&rsquo;t treat your web visitors like academics who love reading challenging and complicated texts. Don&rsquo;t treat your web visitors like lawyers poring over small print. Don&rsquo;t be wordy. And don&rsquo;t show off your extensive vocabulary.</p><p>Instead make your text as simple as possible.</p><p>Don&rsquo;t try to be everything to everybody. Know who you are and what you do.</p><p>If your positioning is clear, it&rsquo;s much easier to stand out on the web and to be found. If your message is clear, it&rsquo;s much easier to create persuasive web copy.</p><p>Be clear. Be specific. Be bold.</p>';
		$task->user_id = 1;
		$task->save();

		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Wireframe";
		$task->body = '<p><a href=\"https://gomockingbird.com/home\">https://gomockingbird.com/home</a></p><h2>1. Know the level</h2><p>By definition, ours at least anyway, a wireframe is a &lsquo;visual representation of a user interface&rsquo;. There&rsquo;s a lot in that, so it&rsquo;s important to understand how &lsquo;real&rsquo; a wireframe needs to be:</p><h3>Sketches</h3><p>How do sketches help you? First of all, they are <strong>quick</strong> and <strong>easy to iterate</strong>. They also enable <strong>experimentation</strong> and are a great solution if you want to receive rapid <strong>feedback</strong>. &nbsp;</p><h3>Lo-fidelity</h3><p>How do lo-fi wireframes help you? They&rsquo;re good for <strong>blocking out key content areas</strong> and <strong>testing the flow</strong> within and across pages. They can be also <strong>clickable</strong>, which is great for testing.</p><h3>Hi-fidelity</h3><p>How do hi-fidelity wireframes help you? They&rsquo;re great because they shouldn&rsquo;t need explanation. They contain <strong>detailed content</strong>, show the <strong>intended behaviours</strong> and are often <strong>clickable</strong>. Hi-fidelity wireframes take longer to create, but they give the chance to get <strong>detailed feedback</strong> from users.</p><h2>2. Cover the basics</h2><p>What is the business looking to achieve with its new website, what are the objectives?</p><p>Who are the intended users and what are their needs and goals?</p><p>What does the business want the user to do?</p><p>In the excitement of creating visual design or writing code these questions are often overlooked. The answers are fundamental though. The better your understanding the greater the chance you&rsquo;ll design something valuable.</p><h2>3. List the elements</h2><p>Identify the pages on the site by walking through the steps the user goes through to meet the desired actions or tasks. Now list the page elements - thestandard ones, such as headers, footers, content areas, menus. And the non-standard ones, such as a calendar, RSS feed or Twitter feed.</p><p>A matrix can be a useful way of seeing at a glance, which elements go on what page.</p><h2>4. Remember you&rsquo;re a user&nbsp;too</h2><p>Whilst you may not have a wealth of wireframing experience, you do have a lot of experience of being a visitor to a site. Draw upon the sites you hold in high regard - why do they work, can you do what you need to quicker or easy, maybe it&rsquo;s just enjoyable to use.</p><p>And what about those sites that drive you crazy - is it because they don&rsquo;t seem to get you? Maybe things are in strange places or the process for doing what you need to seems to long or complicated.</p><p>Have a look at the landscape, the comparator sites in your sector as well as those in others. Inspiration comes from surprising places, so cast the net wide then see what you think works well or could be improved.</p><h2>5. Get your thoughts down</h2><p>There are a lot of options for creating wireframes. These range from pencil and paper sketches to tools for creating real life web pages.</p><p>The purpose of the wireframe should inform the approach you take. Sketches work well in an internal setting &nbsp;(which can include clients). In an external setting, Protoshare or Visio can help you produce something more suitable.</p><h2>6. Sweat the insights</h2><p>Website analytics and customer enquiries (amongst others) can be a rich source of intelligence. Having data on the popular content, as well as what and how customers ask for help means you have a source to check your recommendations against. User research also has a key part to play and can fit well by providing the stories behind the number, i.e. the why to the what.</p><h2>Boiling it all down</h2><p>The most important thing is to know what you&rsquo;re trying to achieve for the business and the users.</p><p>Identify elements by stepping through user journeys.</p><p>Draw upon your own experiences of what works and what doesn&rsquo;t.</p><p>Roll your sleeves up and start creating, then share with others and reiterate.</p><p>You&rsquo;ll end up with a site that not only looks good, but functions well and satisfies the needs of your users.</p>';
		$task->user_id = 1;
		$task->save();

		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Prepare and issue content template";
		$task->body = '<ol class=\"steps-b h3-r\"><li><h3>INTRODUCE YOUR TOPIC</h3><p>Tell people what you\'re talking about and why they\'ll be interested in it.</p><img src=\"https://quicksprout-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/themes/quicksprout/cm-guide/images/06/example-4.png\" alt=\"Example #4\" width=\"358\" height=\"83\" /></li><li><h3>GIVE AN EXAMPLE</h3><p>The subhead may be the product name, as in this example from Houzz.com.</p><img src=\"https://quicksprout-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/themes/quicksprout/cm-guide/images/06/example-5.png\" alt=\"Example #5\" width=\"312\" height=\"203\" /><p><a href=\"http://www.houzz.com/ideabooks/7313761/list/Guest-Picks--Beautiful-Backsplash-Tiles-for-Every-Budget\">http://www.houzz.com/ideabooks/7313761/list/Guest-Picks--Beautiful-Backsplash-Tiles-for-Every-Budget</a></p><p>Or it could be a method or concept. This one, from Mashable, gives a general idea, followed by a specific resource:</p><img src=\"https://quicksprout-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/themes/quicksprout/cm-guide/images/06/example-6.png\" alt=\"Example #6\" width=\"420\" height=\"129\" /><p><a href=\"http://mashable.com/2013/02/15/watch-asteroid-2012-da14-online/\">http://mashable.com/2013/02/15/watch-asteroid-2012-da14-online/</a></p><p>Pictures aren\'t necessary in the Example format, but if your example is visual, pictures can help clarify your points.</p></li><li><h3>EVALUATE IT</h3><img class=\"alignright\" src=\"https://quicksprout-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/themes/quicksprout/cm-guide/images/06/example-7.png\" alt=\"Example #7\" width=\"135\" height=\"167\" /><p>After you give an example, talk about it. Include a few sentences about why you like it <em>(or don\'t like it)</em>, why it works, or how your readers can get it.</p></li><li class=\"padding-t\"><h3>REPEAT WITH REMAINING EXAMPLES</h3><p>Follow the same format for all your examples. There is no right number of examples to use. We\'ve seen posts that focused on two examples, and we\'ve seen posts that give 20 or more.</p><p>In general, in short-form content, the fewer examples you provide, the longer <em>(or more detailed)</em> your evaluation. In long-form content, you have the space to provide a lot of examples and in-depth evaluation.</p></li><li><h3>CONCLUSION/CALL TO ACTION</h3><img class=\"alignright\" src=\"https://quicksprout-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/themes/quicksprout/cm-guide/images/06/example-8.png\" alt=\"Example #8\" width=\"256\" height=\"151\" /><p>Many example posts leave this off. But you can make your content stand out if you\'ll wrap it up for your readers. End your article with:</p><ul class=\"dots\"><li>A summary of the examples you\'ve shown.</li><li>Your opinion.</li><li>Advice to your readers.</li><li>A question.</li></ul><p>Then include your call to action. Ask for comments or social shares. Or tell people to visit another page on your website.</p></li></ol>';
