		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Manual DB Back up";
		$task->body =  '<h2>&nbsp;</h2><h2>How to Backup Your WordPress Database Manually</h2><p>Now that we have a fresh copy of your WordPress files, let&rsquo;s backup your WordPress database, so we can have a full backup that will come in handy on that proverbial rainy day. This is also so easy you will be backing up your site whenever without breaking a sweat.</p><p>Just navigate to your cPanel and locate phpMyAdmin. It&rsquo;s usually located under&nbsp;<em>Database Tools:</em></p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-36113\" title=\"How To Backup Your WordPress Site Choose PhpMyAdmin\" src=\"http://mainwpex.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-choose-phpMyAdmin.jpg\" alt=\"how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-choose-phpMyAdmin\" width=\"750\" height=\"464\" /></p><p>Log in, which should lead you to the phpMyAdmin administration panel:</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-36114\" title=\"How To Backup Your WordPress Site PhpMyAdmin Admin Area\" src=\"http://mainwpex.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-phpMyAdmin-admin-area.jpg\" alt=\"how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-phpMyAdmin-admin-area\" width=\"750\" height=\"474\" /></p><p>Hit the&nbsp;<em>Databases&nbsp;</em>tab to list your databases. If you installed your WordPress site using third-party platforms such as Softaculous or Mojo Marketplace, you might have no idea which database to work with. Same case applies if you have several databases with funny names like mine in the image above. What to do?</p><p>From your File Manager, navigate to your WordPress directory and locate the wp-config.php file. Right-click on wp-config.php and choose view:</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-36115\" title=\"How To Backup Your WordPress Site View Wp Config File For Db Name\" src=\"http://mainwpex.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-view-wp-config-file-for-db-name.jpg\" alt=\"how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-view-wp-config-file-for-db-name\" width=\"750\" height=\"461\" /></p><p>In the window that opens, you want to locate this line:</p><div id=\"highlighter_54181\" class=\"syntaxhighlighter  \"><div class=\"lines\"><div class=\"line alt1\"><table><tbody><tr><td class=\"number\"><code>1</code></td><td class=\"content\"><code class=\"plain\">define(\'DB_NAME\', \'database_name\');</code></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></div><p>Your database name is the value contained in the second set of single quotation marks, which is &lsquo;database_name&rsquo; in our example above. Armed with this info, locate your database in phpMyAdmin.&nbsp;Click on the database to open it. You should see something such as:</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-36116\" title=\"How To Backup Your WordPress Site Open Database\" src=\"http://mainwpex.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-open-database.jpg\" alt=\"how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-open-database\" width=\"750\" height=\"479\" /></p><p>Select all the tables you&rsquo;d like to backup by ticking the checkboxes. Click &ldquo;Check All&rdquo; at the bottom to select all at once. Once you&rsquo;ve selected the tables, hit the&nbsp;<em>Export&nbsp;</em>tab.&nbsp;Select the export method, and set format to SQL:</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-36118\" title=\"How To Backup Your WordPress Site Exporting Database\" src=\"http://mainwpex.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-exporting-database1.jpg\" alt=\"how-to-backup-your-wordpress-site-exporting-database\" width=\"750\" height=\"476\" /></p><p>Hit the&nbsp;<em>Go&nbsp;</em>button, and save your &nbsp;database in a secure folder on your PC. Remember to save copies in the same locations you saved copies of your WordPress files. And that&rsquo;s it, you now have a full backup of your WordPress site.</p><p>Using a different setup? If your host doesn&rsquo;t provide cPanel, please check out this <a title=\"WordPress Backup Post At The Codex\" href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/WordPress_Backups#Database_Backup_Instructions\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress backup post at the Codex</a>.</p><p><strong>Tip:&nbsp;</strong>Create regular backups depending on the frequency of posting to your WordPress site. If you post 50+ posts per day, you need to create backups more regularly than the guy who posts once a month. Other than that, consider checking if your web host offers a reliable backup solution.</p><p>Moving on, let&rsquo;s automate WordPress backups using a couple of nifty WordPress backup plugins. I&rsquo;m all for manual backups because that way you&rsquo;re in complete control. All the same, here&rsquo;s a great list of the best WordPress plugins out there.</p><h2>&nbsp;</h2><h2>&nbsp;</h2>';
		$task->user_id = 1;
		$task->save();

		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Manual File Back up";
		$task->body =  '<h2>Backing Up Your WordPress Files Manually</h2><p>Your WordPress directory contains sub-folders e.g. wp-content, wp-includes etc and files e.g. wp-config.php, theme and plugin files etc required by your WordPress site. The wp-content folder contains all your themes, plugins, cache and uploads among other things. You cannot afford to lose this data.&nbsp;The wp-admin carries all the files required by your WordPress admin area, so you can&rsquo;t afford to lose this as well. The wp-includes folder contains WordPress core files. This is the folder where all the major WordPress code lives. You definitely don&rsquo;t want to lose this code.</p><p>To create a copy of your WordPress files, you just need to download your entire WordPress directory. How?&nbsp;You can login to your server via cPanel or using a FTP program such <a title=\"FileZilla\" href=\"https://filezilla-project.org/\" target=\"_blank\">FileZilla</a>&nbsp;or<a title=\"Transmit\" href=\"https://panic.com/transmit/\" target=\"_blank\">Transmit</a>.</p><h2>Backup Your WordPress Site via cPanel</h2><p>This is so easy you can do it in the time it takes to brew a mug of coffee. Here&rsquo;s the procedure:</p><ul><li>Login to your web host and navigate to cPanel. For most web hosts, the cPanel is usually the first page you encounter when you login</li><li>Navigate to the File Manager, which should lead you to your&nbsp;<em>public_html&nbsp;</em>or&nbsp;<em>Home&nbsp;</em>directory</li><li>From here, just locate your WordPress directory. This is the folder you&nbsp;want&nbsp;to backup</li><li>Unfortunately, you can&rsquo;t download the WordPress folder in File Manager without first compressing it. Worry not though, compressing a folder needn&rsquo;t be challenging</li><li>Click on your WordPress directory, and select <em>Compress&nbsp;</em>from the menu bar. Alternatively, right-click on the folder and choose&nbsp;<em>Compress&nbsp;</em>from the drop-down options menu that appears</li><li>Choose the compression type e.g. ZIP, Tar, GZIP etc from the dialog box that opens. I always go with a ZIP archive</li><li>Then just hit the&nbsp;<em>Compress File(s)&nbsp;</em>button and wait for the process to run its course. Your server will save your compressed WordPress folder</li><li>Click on the archive you just created and choose&nbsp;<em>Download&nbsp;</em>from the menu. Alternatively, right-click on the archive and choose&nbsp;<em>Download.</em></li><li>Choose a secure location on your hard disk and save your backup</li><li>And that&rsquo;s it!</li></ul><p><strong>Tip:&nbsp;</strong>Upload the backup to your Dropbox account, Google Drive, burn it to a DVD/CD, email it etc &ndash; just make sure you have several copies to ensure you don&rsquo;t lose your site should one of the backup dies.</p><p>If your web host uses a different control panel e.g. vDeck, Plesk, etc, you just need to locate your File Manager, and just follow the process i.e.&nbsp;<strong>Locate File Manager -&gt; Locate your WordPress directory -&gt; Compress -&gt; Download. </strong>Repeat regularly.</p><h2>Backing up Your WordPress Files using FTP</h2><p>I use, love and recommend <a title=\"FileZilla\" href=\"https://filezilla-project.org/\" target=\"_blank\">FileZilla</a> because it&rsquo;s lightweight and easy to use. All you have to do is login to your&nbsp;server, locate your WordPress directory, and download the files to your computer. Oh by the way, you need a FTP account to use FTP, which should be easy to set up from FTP manager in your cPanel. Simple as ABC. Don&rsquo;t forget to make copies of your backups.</p>';
		$task->user_id = 1;
		$task->save();

		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Clean Kitchen";
		$task->body = '<h3>1. Clear The Decks!</h3><p>Put away all of the items that belong in the kitchen but are not in their proper place. Then move on to gathering all the items that do NOT&nbsp;belong in the kitchen. Put all these items into a basket to be put away later (or if you have a helper, enlist their help with this.) Do not stop working on the kitchen to take these misplaced items to their homes.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29158 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-8.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-8.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-8-300x168.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"196\" /></p><h3>2. Start At The Sink</h3><p>Put all of the dirty dishes in the dishwasher. Run a sink of hot, soapy water then drop in things that need soaking like the microwave turntable, the dish drainer, or large pans and bowls.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29157 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-6.jpg\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"300\" height=\"233\" /></p><h3>3. Spray Countertops and Stovetop</h3><p>Use an all purpose cleaner and spray surfaces liberally. Let the cleaner do it&rsquo;s work while you move on.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29159 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-9.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-9.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-9-300x246.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"287\" /></p><h3>4. Empty The Refrigerator</h3><p>Well, not completely. Toss anything that is expired and throw the dirty food containers in the sink full of soapy water. Working from top to bottom, wipe down the shelves with a rag sprayed with all-purpose cleaner.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29160 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-10.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-10.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-10-300x209.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"244\" /></p><h3>5.&nbsp;Start At The Top</h3><p>Knocking dirt and debris onto the floor is OK because you&rsquo;re going to be sweeping it all up later. Use a long-handled duster and work your way around the entire perimeter of the room. Clean the corners, the light fixtures, and the tops of the cabinets. Don&rsquo;t forget the top of the refrigerator. When you&rsquo;ve worked your way back to where you started, you&rsquo;re ready to move on.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29168 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-17.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-17.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-17-300x248.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"289\" /></p><h3>6. Wipe Down Upper Cabinets &amp; Clean Microwave</h3><p>Set a wet sponge in the microwave and &ldquo;cook&rdquo; for 2 minutes. While the microwave is doing it&rsquo;s work, dip a rag in the warm, soap water and use it to wipe down the doors and pulls of the upper cabinets and anything else on the wall as you circle the room. The sponge in the microwave should be cool enough to handle now. Use it to wipe down the inside and outside of the microwave.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29162 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-12.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-12.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-12-300x201.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"234\" /></p><h3>7. Wipe Down Countertops and Stovetop</h3><p>Now that the cleaner has had a chance to work, wipe down the horizontal surfaces. Again, just let dust, crumbs, etc. fall to the floor because you&rsquo;ll get it later. Add a little baking soda for stubborn stains. For granite countertops use my <a href=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/2012/06/diy-homemade-granite-cleaner.html\" target=\"_blank\">Homemade Granite Cleaner</a>. For stainless steel surfaces, use my <a href=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/2012/04/how-to-clean-your-stainless-steel.html\" target=\"_blank\">Stainless Steel Cleaner</a>.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29163 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-13.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-13.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-13-300x200.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"233\" /></p><h3>8. Clean Vertical Surfaces of Appliances</h3><p>Use another rag dipped in the warm soapy water to wipe down the front of the refrigerator, dishwasher and oven. Pay close attention to handles and outside edges. (Use my <a href=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/2012/04/how-to-clean-your-stainless-steel.html\" target=\"_blank\">Stainless Steel Cleaner</a> or vinegar diluted with water for stainless steel appliances.)</p><h2><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29161 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-11.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-11.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-11-300x267.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"311\" /></h2><h3>9. Wipe Down Lower Cabinet Doors &amp; Drawers</h3><p>Once again, a rag dipped in warm, soapy water will do the job.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29164 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-14.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-14.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-14-300x189.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"221\" /></p><h3>10. Finish Dishes and Clean Sink</h3><p>Place the items that have been soaking in the sink into the dishwasher or wash by hand. Drain the sink and rinse with hot water. Clean the basin with a mild abrasive like baking soda, or if you need a little more power, I like <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000V72992/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B000V72992&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=onegoodthingbyjillee-20&amp;linkId=2LVNJEJ73KZYAEX6\" target=\"_blank\">Bar Keepers Friend</a>. Rinse with hot water again. Wipe down the faucet and handles with a microfiber cloth.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29166 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-16.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-16.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-16-300x244.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"285\" /></p><h3>11. Empty The Trash</h3><p>Give the inside of the can a quick wipe down with a wet rag before replacing the bag.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29165 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-15.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-15.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-15-300x174.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"203\" /></p><h3>12. Sweep &amp; Mop The Floor</h3><p>Using a broom or a dry duster, get right up to the baseboards, under the cabinets and into the corners. Pull out appliances if necessary. Follow up with a mop or steam cleaner. Start at the farthest corner from the entrance to the room. If using a mop, be sure to use a bucket. You don&rsquo;t want to contaminate your clean sink. Dump the dirty water outside or in the toilet.</p><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29170 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-18.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-18.jpg 350w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-18-300x169.jpg 300w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"350\" height=\"197\" /></p><p>Now it&rsquo;s time to congratulate yourself on a job well done!&nbsp;Grab a cold beverage of your choice and relax&hellip;you&rsquo;ve earned it!!</p><p><strong>A Few Extra Tips:</strong></p><ul><li>Make cleaning up the kitchen a family affair. Divide the steps between your family members, and you really can have the kitchen done in a short time.</li><li>Train your family members to clear and rinse their own plates after each meal. This simple act takes little time for each person, but saves so much time for the dish person later.</li><li>Run a sink of hot soapy water before food preparation begins. As mixing bowls, cutting boards, knives, etc, become dirty, quickly wash them up to prevent food from drying and sticking.&nbsp;It will take the stress out of cooking and you won&rsquo;t be left with a pile of dirty dishes when you&rsquo;re done!</li></ul><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-29173 pib-hover-img\" src=\"http://onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-20.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 457px) 100vw, 457px\" srcset=\"http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-20.jpg 457w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-20-195x300.jpg 195w, http://www.onegoodthingbyjillee.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Clean-Your-Kitchen-20-228x350.jpg 228w\" alt=\"Clean Your Kitchen \" width=\"457\" height=\"702\" /></p>';
		$task->user_id = 1;
		$task->save();

		$task = new App\Task;
		$task->status = 'published';
		$task->title = "Clean Bathroom";
		$task->body = '<p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://core.cleanipedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/how-to-clean-toilet.jpg\" /></p><ol><li>First, put on your gloves and get your toilet cleaning product ready.</li><li>Next, lift up the seat, and apply a small amount of toilet cleaner to the rim.</li><li>Move onto the bowl &ndash; squirt some of your cleaning solution in, and scrub the whole thing thoroughly with the brush, including beneath the rim.</li><li>If there are any stubborn stains or limescale, you&rsquo;ll need to opt for a specialist product for the entire process &ndash; try using something like Domestos Zero Limescale to tackle problems associated with hard water areas, or Total Blast for tough dirt. Follow the product instructions for the best results.</li><li>Remember to scrub the entire inside of the toilet thoroughly, including right into the u-bend. This will help remove any lingering smells.</li><li>Once you&rsquo;re done with the inside, spray both sides of the seat and lid with anti-bacterial spray, and wipe them down with multi purpose wipes. Do the same to the rest of the outside of the toilet.</li></ol><p>There you have it &ndash; a clean fragrant toilet, with no fuss. Easy!</p><p>&nbsp;</p>';
		$task->user_id = 1;
		$task->save();





     	
    }
}
